SIMPLE: pestilence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pestilence
<hw>Pes"ti*lence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pestilence</ets>, L. <ets>pestilentia</ets>. See
<er>Pestilent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Specifically, the disease
known as the plague; hence, any contagious or infectious epidemic
disease that is virulent and devastating.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>pestilence</qex> that walketh in darkness.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xci. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: That which is pestilent, noxious, or
pernicious to the moral character of great numbers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll pour this <qex>pestilence</qex> into his ear.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pestilence weed</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the
butterbur coltsfoot (<spn>Petasites vulgaris</spn>), so called because
formerly considered a remedy for the plague.</cd> <rj><au>Dr.
Prior.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pestilent</ent>⟦br⟧
